statistical analysis

assumptions 

  - Data is normally distributed, when we plot even if it doesn't look like a normal distribution we have to assume it as a normal distribution

  - central limit theorem tells us that given a sufficiently large sample size from a population with a finite level of variance,the means of the samples will be approximately normal distributed.

one way anovo

Hypothesis to compare P_radius across Classes N,H,S 

Null Hypothesis

The mean of the dependent variable is same among the Classes - N,H,S

Alternate Hypothesis

The mean of the dependent variable is not same among the Classes - N,H,S

Test for significance If P value is less than significant level , reject the null hypothesis if P values is greater than significant level, failed to reject null hypothesis

why 1 way ANOVA?

we have to compare mean differences between groups anova uses f test to statistically test the equality

In [5]:
s1_df = df_p1

mean_df = pd.DataFrame()
NY= pd.DataFrame({'Class' : 'N', 'Mean' : s1_df[s1_df.Class.eq('N')].P_radius })
SF = pd.DataFrame({'Class' : 'H', 'Mean' :  s1_df[s1_df.Class.eq('H')].P_radius })

EU = pd.DataFrame({'Class' : 'S', 'Mean' : s1_df[s1_df.Class.eq('S')].P_radius })

mean_df = mean_df.append(NY)
mean_df = mean_df.append(SF)
mean_df = mean_df.append(EU)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (8,7))
sns.boxplot(x = 'Class', y = 'Mean', data = mean_df )
import statsmodels.api as sm
from statsmodels.formula.api import ols
mod = ols ('Mean ~ Class', data = mean_df).fit() 
aov_table = sm.stats.anova_lm(mod,typ = 1)
aov_table['PR(>F)'] = aov_table['PR(>F)'].apply(lambda x : float(x))

pval = float( "{:.7f}". format(aov_table.loc['Class','PR(>F)']))

print("aov_table",aov_table)

if pval<0.05:
    print("\n\nreject null hypothesis :The mean of the dependent variable same among the Classes. ")
else:
    print("\n\nfailed to reject null hypothesis : The mean of the dependent variable same among the Classes.")

Hypothesis testing to identify if there is a difference in S_slope among classes N and H are equal

Null Hypothesis

S_slope among classes N and H are equal



Alternate Hypothesis

S_slope among classes N and H are not equal


Test for significance
If P value is less than significant level , reject the null hypothesis
if P values is greater than significant level, failed to reject null hypothesis


why?
t-test is appropriate when the size of the sample is not more than 30 units


I used equal_var = False in T test
since population variance is not equal as mentioned above [Welch’s t-test]

I used two sided for alternative parameter in Z test sincr

from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
X, y = XScaled,y_scaled
# The scorers can be either one of the predefined metric strings or a scorer
# callable, like the one returned by make_scorer
#scorer = make_scorer(recall_score, average = 'weighted')
scoring = { 'Recall': make_scorer(recall_score,labels = [2,0], average='weighted')}

# Setting refit='AUC', refits an estimator on the whole dataset with the
# parameter setting that has the best cross-validated AUC score.
# That estimator is made available at ``gs.best_estimator_`` along with
# parameters like ``gs.best_score_``, ``gs.best_params_`` and
# ``gs.best_index_``
gs = GridSearchCV(KNeighborsClassifier(),
                  param_grid={
    'n_neighbors':[3,5,7,9,11,13,15,17],
    'weights' : ['uniform','distance'],
    'metric' : ['euclidean','manhattan']
   
    
},
 
                  scoring=scoring, refit='Recall', return_train_score=True)
print(scoring)
gs.fit(X, y)

results = gs.cv_results_
print("best index ",gs.best_index_)
print("best_score_",gs.best_score_)
print("best_estimator_",gs.best_estimator_)
print("best_params_",gs.best_params_)
print("best_estimator_",gs.best_estimator_)
#print("n_neighbors",gs_results.n_neighbors_)

plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
plt.title("GridSearchCV evaluating using multiple scorers simultaneously",
          fontsize=16)

plt.xlabel("n_neighbors")
plt.ylabel("Score")

ax = plt.gca()
ax.set_xlim(2, 19)
ax.set_ylim(0.68, 1)

# Get the regular numpy array from the MaskedArray
X_axis = np.array(results['param_n_neighbors'].data, dtype=int)

for scorer, color in zip(sorted(scoring), ['r', 'b']):
    for sample, style in (('train', '--'), ('test', '-')):
        sample_score_mean = results['mean_%s_%s' % (sample, scorer)]
        sample_score_std = results['std_%s_%s' % (sample, scorer)]
        ax.fill_between(X_axis, sample_score_mean - sample_score_std,
                        sample_score_mean + sample_score_std,
                        alpha=0.1 if sample == 'test' else 0, color=color)
        ax.plot(X_axis, sample_score_mean, style, color=color,
                alpha=1 if sample == 'test' else 0.7,
                label="%s (%s)" % (scorer, sample))

    best_index = np.nonzero(results['rank_test_%s' % scorer] == 1)[0][0]
    #best_index1= np.nonzero(results['rank_test_%s' % scorer] == 1)[0][0]
    best_score = results['mean_test_%s' % scorer][best_index]

    # Plot a dotted vertical line at the best score for that scorer marked by x
    ax.plot([X_axis[best_index], ] * 2, [0, best_score],
            linestyle='-.', color=color, marker='x', markeredgewidth=3, ms=8)
    
   # ax.plot([X_axis[best_index1], ] * 2, [0, best_score],
            #linestyle=':', color=color, marker='*', markeredgewidth=3, ms=8)

    # Annotate the best score for that scorer*
    ax.annotate("%0.2f" % best_score,
                (X_axis[best_index], best_score + 0.005))

plt.legend(loc="best")
plt.grid(False)
plt.show()
  • Grid Search parameter is designed with a scoring Parameter as Recall
  • Recall for class [0 and 2] is metioned to focus on class labels Type H and Type S
  • It returned 7 as best parameter, lets check the recall score for class -Type H and Type S
  • Our intention is to reduce false Negative rate in Class Type H and Type S
  • Cost of Error in False Negative rate for Class Type H and Type S is higher tha Type N

why Recall is Important Metric for Disease Identification

        - Cost Of Error for False Negative is high in Disease Identification especially for Class Type H and Type S         - lets lookout for a model with the highest recall score for classes Type H and Type S

from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve
from numpy import sqrt,argmax
logit_roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test,NNH.predict_proba(X_test), multi_class='ovr')

Best Model and Why ?

Choosing KNeighborsClassifier(metric='euclidean', n_neighbors=9, weights='distance')

  • Why? it has good recall score for classes Type H and Type S
  • cost of error is high for false negative in disease detection and best metric for False Negative rate is Recall
  • best Recall score out of all possibilities for Type H is 0.97
  • best Recall score out of all possibilities for Type s is 0.80
  • the best Recall score is obtaines when Choosing KNeighborsClassifier(metric='euclidean', n_neighbors=9, weights='distance')
  • Knn with Neighbour 7 is also good, but the recall for Class S is lesser compared to the above suggested model

veracity
 -  It would be good if we can understand the source of data for authenticity understanding  
velocity

Statistical Analysis - Hypothesis Testing¶

Hypothesis to compare proportion of companies that are operating between winners and contestants 

Null Hypothesis

proportion of   loan takers  b/w hidden score 2 and 4   are  equal



Alternate Hypothesis

proportion of  loan takers  b/w hidden score 2 and 4 are not equal

Test for significance If P value is less than significant level , reject the null hypothesis if P values is greater than significant level, failed to reject null hypothesis

why 2 proportion Test?
we have to compare 2 categorical sample - 2 proportion test

from statsmodels.stats.proportion import proportions_ztest
no_loan_takers_HS_4 = tab.loc[4,0.0]
no_loan_takers_HS_2 = tab.loc[2,0.0]
n_HS_4 = tab.loc[4,'Total']
n_HS_2 =tab.loc[2,'Total']
stat,pval = proportions_ztest([no_loan_takers_HS_4,no_loan_takers_HS_2],[n_HS_4,n_HS_2 ])
#print (stat,pval)
if pval<0.05:
    print("reject null hypothesis :proportion of  no loan takers  b/w hidden score 2 and 4 are equal ")
else:
    print("failed to reject null hypothesis : proportion of  no loan takers  b/w hidden score 2 and 4 are equall")

Statistical Analysis - Hypothesis Testing¶

Hypothesis to compare proportion of companies that are operating between winners and contestants 

Null Hypothesis

There is no difference in Credit card purchase among loan takers and non loan takers


Alternate Hypothesis

  There is difference in Credit card purchase among loan takers and non loan takers

Test for significance If P value is less than significant level , reject the null hypothesis if P values is greater than significant level, failed to reject null hypothesis

why 2 proportion Test?
We use the chi-square test of independence to find out the difference of categorical variables

In [70]:
import pandas      as pd
import numpy       as np
import scipy.stats as stats

quality_array = np.array([[3177, 1323],[337, 143]])
chi_sq_Stat, p_value, deg_freedom, exp_freq = stats.chi2_contingency(quality_array)

print('Chi-square statistic %3.5f P value %1.6f Degrees of freedom %d' %(chi_sq_Stat, p_value,deg_freedom))
if p_value < 0.05:
    print('Rejecting Null Hypothesis - There is no difference in Credit card purchase among loan takers and non loan takers')
else:
    print('Failed to reject Null Hypothesis - There is no difference in Credit card purchase among loan takers and non loan takers')

from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import precision_score, recall_score,roc_curve
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score,roc_auc_score,f1_score,classification_report,confusion_matrix
clf = LogisticRegression()
grid_values = {'penalty': ['l2'],'C':[0.001,.009,0.01,.09,1,5,10,25]}
scoring = { 'Precision': make_scorer(precision_score,labels = [0.0,1.0], average='binary')}

grid_clf_acc = GridSearchCV(clf, param_grid = grid_values,scoring = scoring,refit='Precision', return_train_score=True)
grid_clf_acc.fit(X_train_b, Y_train_b)

#Predict values based on new parameters
y_pred_b = grid_clf_acc.predict(X_test_b)

# New Model Evaluation metrics 
print('Accuracy Score : ' + str(accuracy_score(Y_test_b,y_pred_b )))
print('Precision Score : ' + str(precision_score(Y_test_b,y_pred_b )))
print('Recall Score : ' + str(recall_score(Y_test_b,y_pred_b )))
print('F1 Score : ' + str(f1_score(Y_test_b,y_pred_b )))

print('Train Accuracy : %.3f'%grid_clf_acc.best_estimator_.score(X_train_b, Y_train_b))
print('Test Accuracy : %.3f'%grid_clf_acc.best_estimator_.score(X_train_b, Y_train_b))
print('Best Accuracy Through Grid Search : %.3f'%grid_clf_acc.best_score_)
print('Best Parameters : ',grid_clf_acc.best_params_)

from sklearn.metrics import precision_recall_curve
yht =model.predict_proba(X_test_b)[:,1]

precision,recall,thresholds = precision_recall_curve(Y_test_b,yht)
precision1,recall1,thresholds1 = precision_recall_curve(Y_test_b,bernoulli_nb.predict_proba(X_test_b)[:,1])
fscore = (2*precision*recall)/(precision+recall)
fscoreNB = (2*precision1*recall1)/(precision1+recall1)
ix = argmax(fscore)
ixnb =argmax(fscoreNB)
print('Best threshold = %f, F-score =%.3f'% (thresholds[ix],fscore[ix]))

no_skill = len(Y_test_b[Y_test_b==1])/len(Y_test_b)
plt.plot([0,1],[no_skill,no_skill],linestyle = '--',label='No skill')
plt.plot(recall,precision,marker='.',label='logistic')
plt.plot(recall1,precision1,marker='*',label='lNB')
plt.scatter(recall[ix],precision[ix],marker='o',color = 'black',label='Best LR')
plt.scatter(recall1[ixnb],precision1[ixnb],marker='*',color = 'black',label='Best NB')
plt.xlabel('Recall')
plt.ylabel('Precision')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Best Model and Why ?

Choosing LogisticRegression(solver="liblinear",C= 0.01, penalty= 'l2')

  • Why? it has good Precision score for class [Customer Identified as Loan on card]
  • cost of error is high for false Positive in Loan detection and best metric for False positive rate is Precision
  • best Precision score out of all possibilities for class ['Loan on Customer'] ==1.0 is is 0.91
  • the best Recall score is obtaines when Choosing KNeighborsClassifierChoosing LogisticRegression(solver="liblinear",C= 0.01, penalty= 'l2')
  • Naive Bayes Model is goood, but the Precision score for class ['Loan on Customer'] ==1.0 is less compared to the suggested model as above
